    "sop": [
      "Standard Operating Procedure (SOP)",
      "Param Automation 3-Phase Digital Motor Starter (Up to 7.5 HP / 22 Amp)This guide is designed to help you correctly install, customize the settings, and safely operate the Param Automation Digital Starter.",
      "Step 1: Installation & Connection",
      "ProcessPower Off: Before installing the starter, completely switch off the main power supply (Main MCB / Kit-Kat Fuse).",
      "Input Connections (Line In): Securely connect the incoming three-phase wires (R, Y, B) from the main line to the input terminals (Line/Input) of the starter.",
      "Output Connections (Motor Out): Connect the three wires coming from the submersible pump or motor to the output terminals (Motor/Output) of the starter.",
      "Ensure Earthing: For safety, always connect the starter body and the motor to a proper earthing system.",
      "Check for Loose Connections: Tighten all screws and terminals properly, as loose connections can cause dangerous sparking.",
      "Step 2: Initial Power On and Display Check",
      "Turn On Supply: Switch on the main power. The digital display screen of the Param Automation starter will light up. Phase Sequence Test (Multi-Protection Check): If the screen shows no error codes and does not display 'Phase Reverse', your connections are in the correct sequence.",
      "PLEASE NOTE: If the three phases (R, Y, B) are not connected in the correct order, the starter will NOT turn ON for safety reasons. It will either display an SPP (Single Phasing Prevention) Error or the display will not come up at all. Therefore, always ensure that the three phases are connected in the correct sequence first. Voltage and Current (Amp) Verification: Once the phase sequence is verified as correct, check the live voltage of all three phases on the screen. This voltage must fall within your motor's safe operating range. Also, check the current load (Amp) as soon as the motor starts running.",
      "Step 3: Customizing Settings",
      "The Param Automation starter is fully customizable. To configure the values, use the normal current (Amp) mentioned on your Motor's Nameplate as your base reference and follow the exact button procedures and timer rules below :",
      "Opening the Setting Mode: To enter the configuration menu, press and hold the SET button for a few seconds. As soon as the settings menu opens on the screen, release the SET button immediately. To navigate to each subsequent setting after this, simply press and release (single press) the SET button once.",
      "Increasing or Decreasing Values: Inside the settings menu, use the Green button to increase a value and the Red button to decrease a value.Amp Standard Base & Critical Warning: Always base your configuration on the normal running amperes written on the motor's nameplate.",
      "SPECIAL ATTENTION: If your motor's nameplate is missing or the ampere value is unreadable, configure your starter's ampere limits based on the standard benchmarks provided in the Amp Guide Chart at the bottom of this document. Setting incorrect values can completely burn out your motor; please do not be careless with this setup. Setting Precise Overload Current (Overload Amp): Take the normal current value from the motor's nameplate (or the guide chart) and multiply it by 1.25 (which sets the overload limit at 25% higher than normal current). Example: If the normal current is 12 Amps, set the overload to 12 × 1.25 = 15 Amps. This saves the motor from burning if it gets jammed. Setting Precise",
      "Dry-Run Current (Dry Run Amp): Take the normal current value from the motor's nameplate (or the guide chart) and multiply it by 0.75 (which sets the dry-run limit at 25% lower than normal current). Example: If the normal current is 12 Amps, set the dry run to 12 × 0.75 = 9 Amps. This ensures the starter detects water loss instantly and shuts down. Dry-Run On-Time Timer (Valid ONLY in AUTO Mode): The unit for this timer is in minutes. The duration you set here (e.g., 120 minutes for 2 hours) dictates how long the starter will wait before automatically restarting the motor after a dry-run trip. Advanced Safety Feature: Upon restarting, if the motor is still running without any load (no water), the starter will run it for only 20 seconds and shut it down immediately. Note that this automated cyclic function works exclusively in Auto Mode. If you operate the motor in Manual Mode, you must manually reset the system after a dry-run trip.",
      "Motor Running Timer (Valid ONLY in MANUAL Mode): The unit for this timer is also in minutes. This feature is used strictly in Manual Mode to run the motor for a fixed duration (e.g., 60 or 120 minutes) after which it automatically shuts off to prevent water or electricity wastage. Please remember that this run-time timer does not function when the starter is set to Auto Mode.",
      "⛈️ Water Protection & Crucial Warranty Clause: This digital starter houses advanced electronic circuitry and must be protected from water and moisture at all costs. During the monsoon season, wrap or cover the starter with a good plastic bag or a waterproof shield to prevent humidity from penetrating the enclosure and damaging the system. Please note that any damage caused by water ingress or moisture exposure will completely void the warranty, and no claims will be entertained.",
      "Step 4: Daily Operation",
      "Auto Mode: If the built-in auto switch is activated, the starter will automatically test the grid voltage when power returns and safely turn on the motor on its own after the pre-programmed time delay.",
      "Manual Mode: To operate the system manually, press the Green button to turn the motor ON and the Red button to turn the motor OFF.",
      "Display Monitoring: Periodically look at the display screen while the motor is operational to ensure it is running smoothly within its designated ampere load limits.",
      "Step 5: Troubleshooting (What to do in case of a Fault)",
      "OVERLOAD or DRY RUN Trip: If the starter trips the motor, the screen will explicitly display an 'Overload' or 'Dry Run' fault indicator.",
      "Resetting the System: Investigate and resolve the underlying cause of the fault before pressing the Reset button.",
      "Important Check: If the starter trips repeatedly, do not force the motor to start. Double-check the water levels inside your borehole and verify the motor's active ampere draw."
    ],
